</note>
<example id="fs-id1168343222232">
<exercise id="fs-id1168344328456"><problem id="fs-id1168344341915">
<para id="fs-id1168344254232">Solve: <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>8</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>9</m:mn><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>31</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168344394992">
<title>Solution</title>
<para id="fs-id1168344126392">Notice, the variable is only on the left side of the equation, so we will call this side the “variable” side, and the right side will be the “constant” side. Since the left side is the “variable” side, the 9 is out of place. It is subtracted from the <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>8</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math>, so to “undo” subtraction, add 9 to both sides. Remember, whatever you do to the left, you must do to the right.</para>
<table id="eip-id1168184743030" class="unnumbered unstyled" summary="This figure has two columns, with written instructions on the left and math on the right. At the top of the figure on the right is the equation 8y minus 9 equals 31. The left side of the equation is labeled “variable”, written in red, and the right side of the equation is labeled “constant”, written in red. One line down on the left, the instructions say: “Add 9 to both sides.” To the right of this sentence is the same equation with 9 being added to both sides: 8y minus 9 plus 9 equals 31 plus 9, with plus 9 written in red on both sides. Another line down on the left, the instructions say: “Simplify.” To the right of this sentence is the equation 8y equals 40. Below this is the text: “The variables are now on one side and the constants on the other. We continue from here as we did earlier.” Two lines down on the left, the instructions say: “Divide both sides by 8.” To the right of this sentence is the same equation being divided by 8 on both sides: 8y over 8 equals 40 over 8, with divided by 8 written in red on both sides. Another line down on the left, the instructions say: “Simplify.” To the right of this instruction is the answer to the equation: y equals 5. Another line down to the left, the instructions say: “Check”. To the right of this word is the original equation again: 8 y minus 9 equals 31. Then the instructions say to substitute 5 for y, and to the right is the equation with 5 substituted in for 5: 8 times 5, with 5 written in red, minus 9 might equal 31. Below this is the equation 40 minus 9 might equal 31. Below this is the equation 31 equals 31, with a check mark next to it.">
<label/><tgroup cols="3">
