<section id="fs-id1168344071798">
<title>Solve Equations with Variables on Both Sides</title>
<para id="fs-id1168344193328">What if there are <term class="no-emphasis">variables</term> on both sides of the equation? For equations like this, begin as we did above—choose a “variable” side and a “constant” side, and then use the subtraction and addition properties of equality to collect all variables on one side and all constants on the other side.</para>
<example id="fs-id1168344198560">
<exercise id="fs-id1168344187326"><problem id="fs-id1168344208617">
<para id="fs-id1168344434721">Solve: <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>9</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>8</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168344282124">
<title>Solution</title>
<para id="fs-id1168344523518">Here the variable is on both sides, but the constants only appear on the right side, so let’s make the right side the “constant” side. Then the left side will be the “variable” side.</para>
<table id="eip-id1168186279317" class="unnumbered unstyled" summary="This figure has two columns, with written instructions on the left and math on the right. At the top of the figure on the right is the equation 9 x equals 8x minus 6. The left side of the equation is labeled “variable”, written in red, and the right side of the equation is labeled “constant”, written in red. One line down on the left, the instructions say: “We don’t want any x’s on the right, so subtract the 8x from both sides.” To the right of this sentence is the same equation with 8x being subtracted from both sides: 9 x minus 8x equals 8 x minus 8 x minus 6, with minus 8 x written in red on both sides of the equal sign. The next line down to the left, the instructions say: “Simplify.” To the right of this instruction is the answer to the equation: x equals negative 6. Another line down to the left, the instructions say: “We succeeded in getting the variables on one side and the constants on the other, and have obtained the solution. Another line down on the left, the instructions say: “Check”. To the right of this instruction is the original equation again: 9 x equals 8 x minus 6. Another line down, the instructions say: “Let x equal negative 6.” To the right of this sentence is the equation with negative 6 substituted in for x: 9 times negative 6, with negative 6 in parentheses and written in red, might equal 8 times negative 6, with negative 6 in parentheses and written in red, minus 6. Below this is the equation negative 54 might equal negative 48 minus 6. Below this is the equation negative 54 equals negative 54, with a check mark next to it.">
<label/><tgroup cols="3">
<colspec colnum="1" colname="c1"/>
<colspec colnum="2" colname="c2"/>
<colspec colnum="3" colname="c3"/>
<tbody>
  <row>
    <entry namest="c1" nameend="c2"/>
    <entry><media id="eip-id1168186279377" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_ElemAlg_Figure_02_03_006e_img_new.jpg"/></media></entry>
  </row>
  <row>
    <entry namest="c1" nameend="c2">We don’t want any <m:math><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:math>’s on the right, so subtract the <m:math><m:mn>8</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:math> from both sides.</entry>
    <entry><media id="eip-id1168186279408" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_ElemAlg_Figure_02_03_006f_img_new.jpg"/></media></entry>
  </row>
  <row>
    <entry namest="c1" nameend="c2">Simplify.</entry>
    <entry><media id="eip-id1168186279429" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_ElemAlg_Figure_02_03_006g_img_new.jpg"/></media></entry>
  </row>
  <row>
    <entry namest="c1" nameend="c3">We succeeded in getting the variables on one side and the constants on the other, and have obtained the solution.</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
    <entry>Check:</entry>
    <entry><media id="eip-id1168186320231" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_ElemAlg_Figure_02_03_006a_img_new.jpg"/></media></entry>
    <entry/>
  </row>
  <row>
    <entry>Let <m:math><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>−6</m:mn></m:math>.</entry>
    <entry><media id="eip-id1168186320259" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_ElemAlg_Figure_02_03_006b_img_new.jpg"/></media></entry>
    <entry/>
  </row>
